{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474314"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:19:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:19:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11984"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11984"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.04,0.77,0.02,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4574"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95017"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4574"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11984"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77991"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1077"},{"type":"tags","id":"1259"},{"type":"tags","id":"2101"},{"type":"tags","id":"2136"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6858"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6862"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28599"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28679"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95017"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 13-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his mother with a three-week history of right groin pain and limp, aggravated by physical activity. He is otherwise well with no recent illness. His BMI is 42 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, his vital signs are within normal limits. He walks with an antalgic gait and externally rotates his right leg during hip flexion. There is limited internal rotation of the right hip, tenderness to palpation, and no erythema. The right leg appears mildly shortened compared to the left.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step to take for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound of the hips","MRI pelvis","AP and frog-leg lateral radiographs of both hips followed by orthopaedic referral","Observation and analgesia for two weeks","Blood tests for inflammatory markers"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation is consistent with a slipped capital femoral epiphysis (SCFE), which is an orthopaedic emergency. SCFE typically affects overweight adolescents (10-16 years) and presents with hip or knee pain, limp, and limited internal rotation of the hip. The patient\u0027s high BMI (42 kg/m\u00b2) is a significant risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAP and frog-leg lateral radiographs of both hips followed by orthopaedic referral\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. Plain radiographs are the initial imaging modality of choice to confirm the diagnosis of SCFE, showing posterior and inferior displacement of the femoral head relative to the femoral neck. Once the diagnosis is confirmed, urgent orthopaedic referral is essential for surgical fixation to prevent progression of the slip and complications such as avascular necrosis of the femoral head.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of the hips\u003C/strong\u003E is often used to assess for hip effusion in conditions like transient synovitis or septic arthritis but is not the appropriate initial imaging modality for suspected SCFE. Ultrasound cannot reliably visualize the bony displacement that characterizes SCFE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E provides detailed evaluation of the femoral head and would be indicated if avascular necrosis is suspected, as in Legg-Calve-Perthes disease. However, it is not the initial imaging modality for SCFE and would unnecessarily delay diagnosis and treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation and analgesia for two weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate for suspected SCFE. Delaying diagnosis and treatment could lead to progression of the slip and increase the risk of complications such as avascular necrosis, chondrolysis, and early osteoarthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood tests for inflammatory markers\u003C/strong\u003E might be useful if septic arthritis or osteomyelitis were suspected. However, the clinical presentation (three-week history, no fever, obesity as a risk factor) is more consistent with SCFE than an infectious process. While inflammatory markers may be part of a broader workup, they should not delay the appropriate imaging and orthopaedic referral.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Slipped capital femoral epiphysis (SCFE) is an orthopaedic emergency requiring urgent diagnosis and surgical fixation to prevent avascular necrosis of the femoral head.","AP and frog-leg lateral radiographs of both hips are the initial imaging modality of choice to diagnose SCFE.","Risk factors for SCFE include obesity, male gender, and adolescent age group (10-16 years)."],"references":["Aronsson DD, Loder RT, Breur GJ, et al. Slipped capital femoral epiphysis: current concepts. J Am Acad Ortho Surg 2006; 14: 666-79.","Nelitz M, Lippacher S, Krauspe R, Reichel H. Perthes disease: current principles of diagnosis and treatment. Dtsch Arztebl Int. 2009 Jul;106(31-32):517-23. doi: 10.3238/arztebl.2009.0517. Epub 2009 Aug 3. PMID: 19730720; PMCID: PMC2735835."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77991"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11984"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77991"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-26T21:04:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-26T21:05:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4574"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95017"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdA